<h3>Lee – Ludwell – Harrison Line (Paternal)</h3>
<p>
  <strong>Key Themes:</strong> Colonial Virginia gentry, political leadership, landholding,
  Anglican church life, literacy, sense of order and responsibility.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Summary (Simplified):</strong><br />
  Early English Lee ancestors in Virginia → intermarriage with Ludwell family →
  connections to Harrison family and broader First Families of Virginia network →
  younger sons and collateral branches move westward into the upland South and frontier →
  line eventually leads to John’s paternal grandfather, Orin Wayne Lee Jr.
</p>

<h3>Brittain Line (Paternal)</h3>
<p>
  <strong>Key Themes:</strong> Welsh origin, military service, frontier settlement,
  discipline, steadiness.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Summary:</strong><br />
  Welsh Brittain ancestors in the Southern frontier → Burrell Brittain (1785–1866),
  War of 1812 veteran → descendants move through the upland South into later generations
  of the Lee family line.
</p>

<h3>Rhyne Line (Paternal)</h3>
<p>
  <strong>Key Themes:</strong> German Carolina settlement, community cohesion, reliability,
  emotional durability.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Summary:</strong><br />
  German immigrant ancestors settle in the Carolinas → Rhyne family establishes itself in
  rural communities → westward movement into Tennessee/Arkansas/Oklahoma region →
  merges with other paternal lines contributing to John’s father’s ancestry.
</p>

<h3>Myrick Line (Maternal)</h3>
<p>
  <strong>Key Themes:</strong> Southern rural life, medicine, service, practical
  intelligence, Texas and Oklahoma settlement.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Summary:</strong><br />
  Myrick ancestors in the South → movement into Texas and Oklahoma → Edwin Richard Myrick
  (E.R.), physician in Hollis, Oklahoma → marriage connections to Swanson, Nicholson, and
  West families → line leads to Ed Myrick and his daughter Sharon Kaye Myrick, John’s
  mother.
</p>

<h3>Rogers – Wilder – Penland Lines (Maternal)</h3>
<p>
  <strong>Key Themes:</strong> Appalachian and Southern upland roots, strong women, family
  cohesion, endurance through hardship.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Summary:</strong><br />
  Families living in Appalachian or upland Southern regions → participation in rural,
  closely knit communities → eventual westward or southward movement into Oklahoma and
  adjacent states → merge with Myrick and other maternal lines, shaping the character of
  John’s maternal heritage.
</p>
